Feature: when bc-container launch fails to bring up a usable session, it writes a host-discoverable diagnostic naming WHY, so the operator can repair it

  Pins lead-2qta. Composes with the launch-time readiness gates that already KNOW
  the failure cause: messaging-db reachability (scenario 33,
  features/bc-launcher/33-launch-gates-on-messaging-db-reachability.gherkin),
  agent-vault reachability (scenario 47,
  features/bc-launcher/47-launch-gates-on-agent-vault-reachability.gherkin), the
  composed two-server readiness barrier (scenario 48,
  features/bc-launcher/48-readiness-barrier-composes-both-supporting-servers.gherkin),
  and the idempotent readiness barrier that gates engage (scenario 34,
  features/bc-launcher/34-launch-runs-idempotent-readiness-barrier-before-engage.gherkin).
  Mirrors the host-discoverability shape of scenarios 13 and 14
  (features/bc-launcher/13-mailbox-readable-from-host.gherkin,
  features/bc-launcher/14-mailbox-response-readable-from-host.gherkin), which make
  a container-side artifact readable from the host.

  Product context: when the in-container agent (Claude) never comes up, there are
  NO tmux sessions to attach to, so the operator — who is on the HOST while the
  failure is inside or around the container — has no surface to diagnose or repair
  against. This scenario pins that a failed launch/engage WRITES A DIAGNOSTIC ERROR
  to a discoverable location surfaced to the host operator, stating WHY the session
  failed to come up.

  The diagnostic location is decided by ADR-041
  (adr/041-launch-failure-diagnostic-is-a-host-readable-file-naming-the-failure-cause.md):
  a persisted, host-readable diagnostic on the SAME host-visible per-BC surface the
  mailbox uses (the scenario-13/14 read-without-attach shape) — NOT stderr-only (cf
  33/47, which is lost on a detached launch) and NOT contingent on "docker logs".
  The BC owns the concrete path; the BC MUST document it and echo the concrete path
  in work_done.

  The diagnostic must be host-discoverable (readable from the host without
  attaching into a session that does not exist) and must DISTINGUISH the failure
  cause wherever the launcher already knows it — agent-vault unreachable (cf 47)
  vs messaging-db unreachable (cf 33) vs readiness barrier never satisfied (cf
  34/48) vs claude/tmux never started. Per ADR-041 D3 the cause is named by a
  LITERAL cause-marker token the operator can grep for; the four tokens below are
  the lead-pinned REQUIRED literals — the BC must emit exactly these strings — so
  the diagnostic points the operator at the right repair rather than at a generic
  "launch failed".

  @scenario_hash:23606a56d6c376b4
  Scenario Outline: a launch that fails to bring up a usable session writes a host-discoverable diagnostic naming the specific failure cause
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And no Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running
    And the launch will fail to bring up a usable session because <fault>
    When I run bc-container launch with BC name "shopsystem-messaging" and a startup prompt
    Then the command exits non-zero
    And no usable tmux session named "agent" is available to attach to in container "bc-shopsystem-messaging"
    And bc-container writes a diagnostic error to a persisted host-discoverable location, on the same host-visible per-BC surface the mailbox uses, stating why the session failed to come up
    And the diagnostic is readable from the host without attaching into the container
    And the diagnostic names the failure cause by carrying the literal cause-marker token "<cause_marker>" exactly, so the operator is pointed at the right repair

    Examples:
      | fault                                                            | cause_marker  |
      | the messaging database at SHOPMSG_DSN is unreachable              | messaging-db  |
      | the agent-vault broker on the shopsystem network is unreachable   | agent-vault   |
      | the readiness barrier never reports both supporting servers ready | readiness     |
      | claude or its tmux session never started inside the container     | agent-startup |

  @scenario_hash:0578c14c4419d169
  Scenario: the diagnostic location is discoverable from the host even when no tmux session ever came up
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And no Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running
    And a launch of BC name "shopsystem-messaging" failed before any usable tmux session named "agent" came up
    When I look for the launch diagnostic from the host
    Then bc-container exposes the diagnostic at a known, documented host-discoverable location on the same host-visible per-BC surface the mailbox uses, per ADR-041
    And the diagnostic is readable from the host without attaching into a tmux session
    And the diagnostic states why the session failed to come up
